Bellabeat Case Study: How Can A Wellness Technology Company Play It Smart?¶

This case study is the Capstone Project of Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate. The 6 steps of Data Analysis is used to present this analysis.

  • Ask
  • Prepare
  • Process (Data Cleaning)
  • Analyze (Data Wrangling)
  • Share (Data Visualization)
  • Act (Recommendation)

Author: Van Nguyen

STEP 1: ASK¶

1.1 Background¶

Bellabeat is a high-tech manufacturer of beautifully-designed health-focused smart products for women since 2013. Inspiring and empowering women with knowledge about their own health and habits, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for females.

The co-founder and Chief Creative Officer, Urka Sren is confident that an analysis of non-Bellebeat consumer data (ie. FitBit fitness tracker usage data) would reveal more opportunities for growth.

1.2 Business Task¶

Analyze FitBit Fitness Tracker Data to gain insights into how consumers are using the FitBit app and discover trends and insights for Bellabeat marketing strategy.

1.3 Business Objectives¶

  • What are the trends identified?
  • How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  • How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

1.4 Deliverables¶

  • A clear summary of the business task
  • A description of all data sources used
  • Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data
  • A summary of analysis
  • Supporting visualizations and key findings
  • High-level content recommendations based on the analysis

1.5 Key Stakeholders¶

  • Urka Sren: Bellabeats cofounder and Chief Creative Officer
  • Sando Mur: Mathematician, Bellabeats cofounder and key member of the Bellabeat executive team
  • Bellabeat marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts guiding Bellabeat's marketing strategy.

STEP 2: PREPARE¶

2.1 Information about the data source¶

Data source: FitBit Fitness Tracker Data: public dataset on Kaggle - Link

Information about dataset:

  • Sample: 30 eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring
  • Data collection: survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016 - 05.12.2016
  • Data Organization and verification: Available to us are 18 CSV documents. Each document represents different quantitative data tracked by Fitbit. Every user has a unique ID and different rows since data is tracked by day and time.

2.2 Limitations of the data Set¶

  • Due to the limitation of size (30 users) and not having any demographic information we could encounter a sampling bias. We are not sure if the sample is representative of the population as a whole
  • Data collected from year 2016. Users' daily activity, fitness and sleeping habits, diet and food consumption may have changed since then, hence data may not be timely or relevant.

2.3 Data selection¶

Focus is on daily usage of the Fitbit device as it should provide a high-level insight on the usage pattern of smart devices. Thus the following files from the dataset has been selected:

  • dailyActivity_merged.csv
  • sleepDay_merged.csv
  • hourlySteps_merged.csv

From the above observation, we can see that:¶

  • There is no typo, Null or missing values.
  • Data frame has 940 rows and 15 columns.
  • ActivityDate is wrongly classified as object dtype and has to be converted to datetime64 dtype.
  • There are 33 unique IDs, instead of 30 unique IDs as expected from 30 fitness tracker users
  • There are 3 duplicates in the 'sleep' dataframe

The following data manipulation is performed:¶

  • Rename 'ActivityDate' from 'daily_activity' and 'SleepDay' from 'sleep' to 'Date' for merging 2 dataframes later on
  • Convert ActivityDate to datatime64 dtype.
  • Remove duplicates in the 'sleep' dataframe
  • Create new column 'DayOfWeek' by separating the date into day of the week for further analysis.
  • Create new columns 'TotalMinute' & 'TotalHour' as the sum of VeryActiveMinutes, FairlyActiveMinutes, LightlyActiveMinutes and SedentaryMinutes.
  • Create new column 'TotalHoursAsSleep' from 'TotalMinuteAsleep'
  • Merge ActivityDate & Sleep dataframes by Id, ActivityDate
  • Rearrange columns for easier reading
  • Split 'ActivityHour' (dtype:datetime) in to 2 columns 'Date' & 'Time'

4.1.1 Percentage of Activitity level in Minutes¶

In [31]:
# Calculate total of individual minutes column
very_active_mins = merged_df['VeryActiveMinutes'].sum()
fairly_active_mins = merged_df['FairlyActiveMinutes'].sum()
lightly_active_mins = merged_df['LightlyActiveMinutes'].sum()
sedentary_mins = merged_df['SedentaryMinutes'].sum()

# Plot the pie chart
slices = [very_active_mins, fairly_active_mins, lightly_active_mins, sedentary_mins]
labels = ["Very active minutes", "Fairly active minutes", "Lightly active minutes", "Sedentary minutes"]

plt.pie(slices, 
        labels = labels, 
        colors = sns.color_palette('pastel'), 
        wedgeprops = {"edgecolor": "black"}, 
        autopct = "%1.1f%%")
plt.title("Percentage of Activity in Minutes")
plt.show()

As seen from the pie chart,

  • Sedentary minutes takes the biggest slice at 81.3%.

  • This indicates that users are using the FitBit app to log daily activities such as daily commute, inactive movements (moving from one spot to another) or running errands.

  • App is rarely being used to track fitness (ie. running) as per the minor percentage of fairly active activity (1.1%) and very active activity (1.7%). This is highly discouraging as FitBit app was developed to encourage fitness.

plt.legend()
plt.show()

According to results published in JAMA Network Open, those who took 7,000 steps or more a day on average were 50 percent to 70 percent less likely to die of any cause over the next decade, compared with those who took fewer steps. In the graphs above we can determine that users walk daily the recommended amount of steps of 7000 except for Sunday's.

4.2.2 Use of smart device - By Usage level¶

Now we need to see how often do the users in our sample use their device. That way we can plan our marketing strategy and see what features would benefit the use of smart devices.

We will calculate the number of users that use their smart device on a daily basis, classifying our sample into three categories knowing that the date interval is 31 days:

  • High use - users who use their device between 21 and 31 days.
  • Moderate use - users who use their device between 10 and 20 days.
  • Low use - users who use their device between 1 and 10 days.
In [41]:
# Calculate how many days each users used the Fitbit Tracker
daily_use = merged_df.groupby(['Id']).count()['Date'].reset_index()
daily_use.columns = ['Id','DayUsed']

# Define function for classifying 'Usage' based on 'DayUsed'
def f(row):
    if row['DayUsed'] <= 10:
        val = 'Low Use'
    elif row['DayUsed'] <= 25:
        val = 'Moderate Use'
    else:
        val = 'High Use'
    return val

# Create new column 'Usage' using the function above
daily_use['Usage'] = daily_use.apply(f, axis = 1)

We need to create a new data frame calculating the total amount of minutes users wore the device every day and creating three different categories:

In [43]:
# Create new column 'Percentage' of Hours used Fitbit Tracker
merged_df['TotalHoursPercentage'] = round(merged_df['TotalHours'] / 24 * 100,2)

# Define function for classifying 'Worn' based on 'TotalHoursPercentage'
def w(row):
    if row['TotalHoursPercentage'] < 50:
        val = 'Less than half day'
    elif row['TotalHoursPercentage'] < 100:
        val = 'More than half day'
    else:
        val = 'All Day'
    return val

# Create new column 'Worn' using the function above
merged_df['Worn'] = merged_df.apply(w, axis = 1)

  • There is no correlation between daily activity level based on steps and the amount of hours users sleep a day.

STEP 5: ACT¶

In the final step, we will be delivering our insights and providing recommendations based on our analysis.

Here, we revisit our business questions and share with you our high-level business recommendations.

1. What are the trends identified?¶

1.1 About users¶

  • Active level: Majority of users (81.3%) use the FitBit app to track sedentary activities instead of using it for tracking their health habits while FitBit app was develeped to encourage fitness.

  • Average daily steps: The average of users walk more than 7,500 steps daily besides Sundays, which meets the goal of walking more than 7,000 daily steps for better health according to the CDC research.

  • Active time: Most activity happens during lunch time from 12pm to 2pm and evenings from 5pm and 7pm, which indicates that people more active in after work time.

  • Average sleep hours: Users sleep less than the recommenation of 8 hours per night.

1.2 How users used the smart device¶

  • Users prefer to track their activities during weekdays as compared to weekends - perhaps because they spend more time outside on weekdays and stay in on weekends.

  • The majority of users (87%) used the device more than 20 days a month. However, only about 50% of user wear the device all day to track their fitness level.

1.3 Correlations¶

  • There is a negative relationship between Sedentary Minutes and Sleep time, which means that higher Sedentary minutes might result in less sleep time.

2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?¶

Both FitBit and Bellabeat develop products focused on providing women with their health, habit and fitness data and encouraging them to understand their current habits and make healthy decisions. These common trends surrounding health and fitness can very well applied to Bellabeat customers.

3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?¶

3.1 Bellabeat's target audience¶

Women who work full-time jobs (according to the hourly intensity data) and spend a lot of time at the computer/in a meeting/ focused on work they are doing (according to the sedentary time data).

These women do some light activity to stay healthy (according to the activity type analysis). Even though they need to improve their everyday activity to have health benefits. They might need some knowledge about developing healthy habits or motivation to keep going.

3.2 Recommendations for Bellabeat app¶

1. Create a Reflect Section: This section provides users with insights about their fitness level & how they are compared to the average or the fitness goals they have set. Hence, they could be encouraged to become more active to achieve their health & fitness goal. From these users personal insights, the app can propose health knowledge related to the user insights. For example, propose the different benefits of walking more than 7,000, 8,000 and 10,000 steps a day when users daily steps are below 7,000.

2. Create an Exercise Section: Suggest different types of exercise for different purpose (ie. simple 10 minutes exercise on weekday and a more intense exercise on weekends, relaxing exercise to enhance sleep, meditation, etc.) and calories intake and burnt rate information on the Bellabeat app.

3. Gamification:

  • Make users fitness goals into game levels with rewards to motivate users to do active activities instead of sedentary activities (ie. Daily/weekly/ monthly calorie burning challenge, Daily steps of 7,000-10,000 steps challenge, Follow the Exercise Plan in Exercise Section, etc.).
  • Reward: Using 'Streak' like Duolingo streak to motivate users (Note: A streak starts at zero and increases by one for each day the user completes a lesson. It resets to zero if the user does not complete a challenge). Reaching certain milestones (such as 100 day streak) can earn the user discounts voucher on other Bellabeat products or health-related products (i.e tumbler, yoga mat, etc.)

4. Notification:

  • Send push notification to remind users to go for a walk or do a short exercise at lunch time & after working hours.
  • User could set up a desired time to go to sleep and receive a notification minutes before to prepare to sleep. Also offer helpfull resources to help customers sleep - ex. breathing advises, podcasts with relaxing music, sleep techniques.

5. Product features As there was just 86% of the users use their device on a daily basis and that just 50% of the users wear the device all time the day they used it. We can continue promote Bellabeat's products features:

  • Water-resistant
  • Long-lasting batteries so that users can wear the products everyday to any occasion without worrying about the battery.
  • Fashion/ elegant products as the target audience are women
